he match here\" (implying customer is stupid) = RUDE\n\n2. MOCKING OR BELITTLING:\n   - Agent making fun of customer's situation\n   - Using clearly sarcastic tone to demean customer\n   - Laughing at customer's problems\n   - Example: \"If that if that you can go ahead and do another post\" (dismissive indifference to threat) = RUDE\n\n3. AGGRESSIVE/HOSTILE TONE:\n   - Agent yelling or using abusive/slangs language. Example Hindi slangs: \"साला\", \"कमीना\", etc. Example english slangs: \"Stupid\", \"Idiot\", \"Dumb\", etc\n   - Threatening customer (beyond standard call disconnection policy)\n\n4. DELIBERATELY UNHELPFUL:\n   - Agent refusing to help when they clearly can and should\n   - Agent lying or providing false information intentionally\n   - Repeatedly deflecting without attempting any resolution\n\n5. CONDESCENDING OR PATRONIZING TONE:\n   - Agent speaking down to customer as if they are inferior\n   - Agent making statements that imply customer is unintelligent or unreasonable\n   - Example: \"I think I know how I am speaking and I think the, I am doing my best\" (defensive and dismissive of valid complaint) = RUDE\n   - Example: \"at least I am not the match\" (implying customer is the problem) = RUDE\n\n6. ARGUMENTATIVE OR COMBATIVE BEHAVIOR:\n   - Agent engaging in back-and-forth argument with customer instead of de-escalating\n   - Agent contradicting themselves while insisting customer is wrong\n   - Agent saying \"Please don't interrupt where I am talking\" while repeatedly interrupting customer = RUDE\n   - Agent getting defensive and making it about themselves rather than solving customer's issue\n\n7. DISMISSIVE OR DISRESPECTFUL RESPONSES:\n   - Agent showing complete indifference to customer's legitimate concerns\n   - Agent encouraging customer to escalate (\"you can go ahead and do another post\") = RUDE\n   - Agent refusing to acknowledge valid points raised by customer\n   - Note: Simply redirecting to merchant/another department is NOT dismissive unless done with clear disrespect\n\n8. DEMANDING/ORDERING CUSTOMER (Non-Policy Related):\n   - Agent demanding customer delete social media posts as precondition for help = RUDE\n   - Agent ordering customer to do something unrelated to resolution\n   - Note: Requesting professional language or warning about call disconnection due to abuse = NOT RUDE (policy enforcement)\n\nIMPORTANT DISTINCTIONS:\n\n**REDIRECTING vs DISMISSIVE:**\n- \"I can only guide you to contact the customer support\" = NOT RUDE (helpful redirect)\n- \"we can't do anything. So what you can do is, you can reach out to the merchant\" THEN refusing to help further when customer objects = BORDERLINE/CONTEXT DEPENDENT\n- If agent tries to help or explains why they can't = NOT RUDE\n- If agent just deflects repeatedly without empathy or attempt = POTENTIALLY RUDE\n\n**CLARIFYING vs ARGUING:**\n- Asking same question 2-3 times when customer hasn't answered clearly = NOT RUDE\n- Getting into extended back-and-forth where agent defends themselves instead of helping = RUDE\n\n**SETTING BOUNDARIES vs BEING RUDE:**\n- \"Please use professional language or we'll disconnect\" = NOT RUDE (policy)\n- \"Please don't interrupt where I am talking\" while repeatedly interrupting customer = RUDE (hypocritical)\n\nEVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS:\n- Quote the specific agent text\n- Explain why it IS or IS NOT rude based on the categories above\n- When marking \"No\", explicitly state which category of acceptable behavior it falls under\n- When marking \"Yes\", specify which rudeness category applies\n- Remember: Professional boundaries, policy enforcement, and honest communication are NOT rudeness\n\nDECISION FRAMEWORK:\n- Ask: \"Is the agent insulting, mocking, being hostile, condescending, argumentative, or dismissive to the customer?\"\n- If NO → Mark as \"No\"\n- If YES → Mark as \"Yes\"\n- Default to \"No\" unless there's clear rudeness\n- Consider the OVERALL pattern: One borderline statement = probably not rud